%N A394756 Decimal expansion of (6*sqrt(3) - Pi)/24.
%C A394756 This constant gives the area of the lune of the argument, according to which Alexander of Aphrodisias wrote that Hippocrates of Chios had erroneously claimed that he could square the circle (see Dunham).
%C A394756 Here, the lune is one of the six crescent-shaped regions formed between the outer semicircles and the boundary of the inner circle when a regular hexagon is inscribed in a circle of radius 1 and outward-facing semicircles are drawn on the hexagon's sides as diameters.
%D A394756 William Dunham, Journey Through Genius, Wiley, 1990, Chapter 1, pp. 20-22.
%H A394756 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_of_Aphrodisias">Alexander of Aphrodisias</a>.
%H A394756 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippocrates_of_Chios">Hippocrates of Chios</a>.
%H A394756 <a href="/index/Tra#transcendental">Index entries for transcendental numbers</a>.
%e A394756 0.302113007992644605112584777739822138...
%t A394756 RealDigits[(6Sqrt[3]-Pi)/24,10,100][[1]]
